               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390204-name-1666" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1666" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1666" type="surname" value="PULLEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1666" type="given" value="GEORGE JAMES"></interp>GEORGE JAMES PULLEN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am servant to Mr. William Pershouse, a coach-master and a farmer, who lives at Greenwich. Some pieces of iron were taken from a wall that was pulled down, and put into a loft of his—the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183902040249"></xptr>
               <p>prisoner had worked there as a labourer—the policeman brought this piece of iron and weight to my master.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390204-name-1667" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1667" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1667" type="surname" value="DENNIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1667" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN DENNIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I made this house-tie for Mr. Pershouse, nearly two years ago—I made three more at the time, and it cost two shillings, or half-a-crown—as old iron, it is worth 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. or 8<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390204-name-1668" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1668" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1668" type="surname" value="WALKER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1668" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN WALKER</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable R</hi> 182.) I met the prisoner with a bag on his back, on Tuesday, the 15th of January—I asked him what he had got there—he said it was no business of mine—I took the bag from him—he ran away, about thirty yards—I then overtook him—he said he had just picked the bag up in the road—it was quite dry, but it was a very muddy night—it contained this 1/4 cwt., and this iron tie.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Did I not say that a man threw it out of the loft for me to sell? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> You said, when yon returned from the Magistrate, that a man named Banks threw it out of the loft, and told you to sell it for old iron—Banks has since absconded.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390204-name-1669" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1669" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1669" type="surname" value="PULLEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1669" type="given" value="GEORGE JAMES"></interp>GEORGE JAMES PULLEN</persName>
                  </hi>. <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> We had a weight of this desorip<lb></lb>tion, and I believe this is it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Was I ever in the loft? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, occasionally, I believe, I and Banks was in the loft.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I picked them op in the road—I had not worked at the place for some time.</p>
